vative efforts that, by 1960, had all but banished the existentialist and pragmatist paradigms—not to mention Marxism—from philosophy departments all across the country, replacing them with an approach that valorized scientific objectivity and free markets and which downplayed the anti-theistic implications of modern thought. As he shows, while there have since been many instances of definitive and even explosive rejection of this conservative trend, its effects can still be seen at American universities today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAcademic freedomzCaliforniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCold War. 0aPhilosophyxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhilosophyxStudy and teachingxPolitical aspectszCaliforniaxHistoryy20th century. 0aUnited States - Intellectual life - 20th century - Political aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aMcCarthyism.  aUCLA.  aphilosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226396415423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226396415/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles